    <h2>SECTION A: Attempt any TWO question.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>What is queuing system ? Explain the elements of queuing system with example.</p>
<p> </p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The line where the entities or customer wait is generally known as a queue. The combination of all entities in the system being served and waiting for service will be called a <strong>queueing system</strong>.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-10960 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/download-4.png?resize=416%2C191&amp;ssl=1" alt="- Hamro CSIT" width="416" height="191" data-recalc-dims="1" /></p>
<p>Elements of the Queuing system are:</p>
<p>a. <strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Calling population</span></strong>: The calling population in the context of a queueing system refers to the set of all entities (individuals, items, tasks, etc.) that have the potential to enter the queue and request service. It represents the source from which entities may arrive and join the queue for service.</p>
<p>b. <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Arrival process</strong></span> : The arrival process in a queueing system describes how entities from the calling population enter the queue over time. Arrival process helps in determining the workload on the system and influences decisions related to queue design, capacity planning, and resource allocation.</p>
<p>c. <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Service Process </strong></span> : The service process in a queueing system describes how entities are served by the system once they enter the queue. Service process is crucial for determining the efficiency of the system, minimizing waiting times, and optimizing resource utilization.</p>
<p>d. <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Queuing Discipline</strong></span> : The rules governing the order in which entities are served. Common disciplines include first-come, first-served (FCFS), last-come, first-served (LCFS), and priority-based service.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">FIFO</span> : FIFO stands for First In First Out. It is a queuing discipline where the first arrived population is served at first. For eg : the first customer entered at shop is served first.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">LIFO</span> : LIFO stands for Last In First Out is a concept of queuing discipline where the last process is served first. for eg : The history of browser, the last exited tab is displayed first in history.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Priority</span> : A special number is assigned to customer in waiting line then accordingly to this number the customer is choosen for the service.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">SIRO</span> : SIRO is short form of Service in Random Order. It is a queuing discipline in which any random process is served. Here, no any algorithm is used to determine which process or population could be next.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">SPT</span> : Service Process Time is the queuing discipline where the population or the process with the shortest time is given the first service .</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the properties of random number ? The sequence of numbers 0.54, 0.73, 0.98, 0.11 and 0.68 has been generated. Use the Kolmogorov Smirnove test with level of significance (α) 0.05 to determine if the hypothesis that the numbers are uniformly distributed on the interval 0 to 1 can be rejected. (Note that the value of D for α = 0.05 ans N = 5 is 0.565).</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Random number are basic ingrudient in simulation of almost all discrete system. Properties of random number are :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Uniformity</span> : The random number generated should be uniform that means a sequence of random number should be equally probable everywhere.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Independent</span> : Each random number should be independent samples that is the current value of random number as no relation with the previous value and it can be drawn from contineous uniform distribution between 0 and 1 i.e f(x) = 1.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Maximum density</span> : Large samples of random numbers should be generated in even range.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Maximum cycle</span> : It state that representation of numbers should be about only after the large interval of time.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Numerical part:</strong></p>
<p>Arranging the numbers in ascending order :</p>
<p>0.11, 0.54, 0.68, 0.73, 0.98</p>
<p>Now,</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">R<sub>i</sub></td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$\frac{{i}}{{N}}$$</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$\frac{{i}}{{N}} &#8211; R_i$$</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;"> $$R_i -\frac{{i-1}}{{N}}$$</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.11</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$\frac{{1}}{{5}} = 0.20$$</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.20 &#8211; 0.11</p>
<p>= 0.09</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$0.11 -\frac{{1-1}}{{5}} = 0.31$$</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.54</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$\frac{{2}}{{5}} = 0.40$$</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.40 &#8211; 0.54</p>
<p>= &#8212;</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$0.54 -\frac{{2-1}}{{5}} = 0.34$$</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.68</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$\frac{{3}}{{5}} = 0.60$$</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.60 &#8211; 0.68</p>
<p>= &#8212;</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$0.68 -\frac{{3-1}}{{5}} = 0.28$$</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.73</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$\frac{{4}}{{5}} = 0.80$$</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.80 &#8211; 0.73</p>
<p>= 0.70</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$0.73 -\frac{{4-1}}{{5}} = 0.13$$</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">0.98</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$\frac{{5}}{{5}} = 1$$</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">1 &#8211; 0.98</p>
<p>= 0.02</td>
<td style="width: 25%; text-align: center;">$$0.98 -\frac{{5-1}}{{5}} = 0.18$$</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Now,</p>
<p>$$D^+ = max(\frac{{i}}{{N}} &#8211; R_i)$$</p>
<p>$$D^+ = max(0.09, 0.70, 0.02)$$</p>
<p>$$D^+ = 0.70$$</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>$$D^- = max(R_i -\frac{{i-1}}{{N}})$$</p>
<p>$$D^- = max(0.31, 0.34, 0.28, 0.13, 0.18)$$</p>
<p>$$D^- = 0.34$$</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>$$D= max(D^+, D^-)$$</p>
<p>$$D= max(0.70, 0.34)$$</p>
<p>$$D= 0.70$$</p>
<p>The computed value of D obtained from the above is 0.70 and the tabulated value from table with α = 0.05 ans N = 5 is 0.565. As the tabulated balue is leaa than the computed value the distribution of random numbers is not  uniform.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>What is a system modeling? What are the steps involved in system modeling.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>System modeling is the process of developing abstract models of a system, with each model presenting a different view or perspective of that system. System modeling includes some steps and they are dealt below with a flowchart.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-39346 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/model-simulation.drawio.png?resize=387%2C1916&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="387" height="1916"></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>fig : flowchart of system modeling</strong></p>
<p>Steps involved in system modeling are:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Problem Formulation:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Clearly define the problem that needs to be addressed using simulation. Identify the objectives and goals of the study.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Setting of Objectives &amp; Overall Project Plan:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Establish specific objectives for the simulation study and create an overall project plan outlining the timeline, resources, and milestones.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Model Conceptualization:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Develop a conceptual model that represents the system being simulated. This involves deciding on the structure and components of the model.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Data Collection:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Gather relevant data to support the model. This includes parameters, inputs, and initial conditions. The data should be accurate and representative of the real system.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Model Translation:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Translate the conceptual model into a formal representation, often using mathematical equations or computational algorithms. Implement the model in a simulation environment.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Verification:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Ensure that the simulation model accurately represents the conceptual model by checking its correctness. Verification involves validating the coding and logic of the model.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Validation:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Validate the simulation model by comparing its outputs to real-world data. This step ensures that the model behaves realistically and provides valid insights into the system.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Experimental Design:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Plan the experiments or scenarios that will be simulated. Define the input variations, conditions, and factors to be tested. Set up the simulation’s boundary conditions.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Production Runs:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Execute the simulation with the specified inputs and conditions. Collect data on the system’s behavior, performance, and other relevant output measures during the production runs.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Repetition of Runs:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Conduct multiple simulation runs to assess the variability and robustness of the model. Repetition helps ensure that the results are consistent and reliable.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Documentation &amp; Report:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Document the simulation study, including the model details, assumptions, data sources, and results. Generate a comprehensive report summarizing the findings and insights.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Implementation:</strong>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Implement the recommendations or decisions based on the simulation results. This may involve changes to the real-world system or the adoption of specific strategies.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<h2>SECTION B: Attempt any EIGHT question.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the application areas of simulation ?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Simulation is the way to represent the real world entity to the virtual environment. It  is a model that mimics the operation of an existing or proposed system to test different scenarios or process changes. Applications of Simulation are :</p>
<p><strong>Manufacturing Application</strong> :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Analysis of electronics assembly operations.</li>
<li>Optimization of cycle time and utilization in semiconductor test manufacturing.</li>
<li>Analysis of storage and retriva strategies in a warehouse.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Construction Engineering</strong> :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Construction of a dam embankment.</li>
<li>Activity scheduling in a dynamic, multi-project setting.</li>
<li>Investigation of the structural steel erection process.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Military Application</strong> :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Modeling military reuirements for non-war fighting operations.</li>
<li>Multi trajectory performance for varying scenario sizes.</li>
<li>Design and test of an intelligent controllers.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Human System</strong> :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Modeling human performance in complex systems.</li>
<li>Studying the human element in our traffic control.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Business Process Simulation</strong> :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Product development program planning.</li>
<li>Reconcillation of business and system modeling.</li>
</ul>
</div>
