<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain Markov chain with suitable example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>If the future states of a process are independent of the past and depend only on the present, the process is called a Markov process. A discrete state Markov process is called a Markov chain. A Markov Chain is a random process with the property that the next state depends only on the current state.</p>
<p>Markov chains are used to analyze trends and predict the future. (Weather, stock market, genetics, product success, etc.</p>
<p><strong>Formally,</strong></p>
<p>A Markov chain is a sequence of random variables X<sub>1</sub>, X<sub>2</sub>, X<sub>3</sub>, &#8230; with the Markov property, namely that, given the present state, the future and past states are independent.</p>
<p>\(P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i_n, x_{n-1} = i_{n-1}, . . ., x_0 = i_0) = P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i_n)\)</p>
<p>The conditional probability above gives us the probability that a process in state i<sub>n</sub> at time n moves to i<sub>n+1</sub> at time n + 1. We call this the transition probability for the Markov chain. If the transition probability does not depend on the time n, we have a stationary Markov chain, with transition probabilities</p>
<p>\(P_{ij} = P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i)\)</p>
<p>Now we can write down the whole Markov chain as a matrix P:</p>
<p>\(P = \begin{bmatrix}<br />
P_11 &amp; P_12 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_1n\\<br />
P_21 &amp; P_22 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_2n\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
P_n1 &amp; P_n2 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_nn\\<br />
\end{bmatrix}\)</p>
<p>Example:</p>
<p>Weather Problem:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>raining today  ⇒ 40 % rain tomorrow</li>
</ul>
<p>⇒ 60 % no rain tomorrow</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>not raining today  ⇒ 20 % rain tomorrow</li>
</ul>
<p>⇒ 80 % no rain tomorrow</p>
<p>What will be the probability if today is not raining then not rain the day after tomorrow?</p>
<p><i>Markov chain diagram:</i></p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-10953 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/download-2.png?resize=334%2C145&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="334" height="145"></p>
<p>\(P^2 = \begin{pmatrix}0.4 &amp; 0.6 \\ 0.2 &amp; 0.8\end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}0.4 &amp; 0.6 \\ 0.2 &amp; 0.8\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>\(= \begin{pmatrix}0.16 + 0.12 &amp; 0.24 + 0.48 \\ 0.08 + 0.16 &amp; 0.12 + 0.64\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>\(= \begin{pmatrix}0.28 &amp; 0.72 \\ 0.24 &amp; 0.76\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>Thus, the probability of not being rainy the day after tomorrow is 0.76.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>Why is GPSS called transaction flow oriented language?</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>GPSS stands for General Purpose Simulation System. It is a discrete time general &#8211; purpose programming language where a simulation clock advances in discrete steps. A system is modeled as transactions enters the system and are passed from one service to another. This is a particularly well suited for modeling queuing system. In GPSS transaction is an object with a number of attributes. A single transaction may represent several individual entities.</p>
<p>GPSS is a highly structured and special purpose simulation language based on process interaction approach and oriented toward queuing system. The system being simulated is described by the block diagram using various GPSS blocks. Each block represents events, delays and other actions that affect the transaction flow. Therefore, GPSS is called transaction flow oriented language.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Why confidence interval is needed in the analysis of simulation output ? How can we establish a confidence interval ?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In the analysis of simulation output, confidence interval is needed because it provide us with upper and lower limit on sample mean, and with this interval we can then be confident we have captured the population mean. The lower limit and upper limit around our sample mean tells us the range of values that our true population mean is likely to lie within.</p>
<p>We can establish confidence interval as follow :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Identify a sample statistic (eg : sample mean, same proportion) that we will use to estimate a population parameter.</li>
<li>Select a confidence level. We can choose 90%, 95%, 99%.</li>
<li>Find the margin of error. It is calculated as margin of error. It is calculated as :</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;">margin of error = Critical value * standard deviation</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">OR</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">margin of error = Critical value * standard error</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>specify the confidence interval as :</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;">Confidence interval = sample statistic ± margin of error</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain Monte carlo simulation.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Monte carlo simulation is a computerized mathematical technique to generate random sample data based on some known distribution for numerical experiments. This method is applied to risk quantative analysis and decision making problems. This method project management, energy, manufacturing, engineering, research and development, transportation etc.</p>
<p>Following are the three important characteristics of Monte &#8211; Carlo method:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The output must generate random samples.</li>
<li>The input distribution must be known.</li>
<li>The result must be known while performing an experiment.</li>
</ul>
<p>Monte &#8211; Carlol simulation depends in following steps :</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Problem Formulation: </strong>Identify a system or process that involves uncertainty or randomness. Define input parameters and their probability distributions.</li>
<li><strong>Random Sampling: </strong>Generate random samples for the input parameters based on their probability distributions. This can be done using random number generators.</li>
<li><strong>Simulation Execution: </strong>Run the simulation model using the randomly generated input values. Record the output or results for each simulation run.</li>
<li><strong>Analysis: </strong>Aggregate the results over multiple simulation runs to obtain statistical measures such as mean, variance, confidence intervals, etc. Analyze the distribution of the output to understand the system’s behavior under different scenarios.</li>
</ol>
<p>For eg :</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>What is three step approach for validation of simulation models ?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>For validation process, there are three steps or approaches which has been widely used :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Build the model that has high face validity.</li>
<li>Validate model assumption.</li>
<li>Compare input output transformation to the input output transformation of real system.</li>
</ul>
<p>a. <strong>Face Validity</strong> :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Build a reasonable model on its face to model users who are knowledgable about the real system being simulated.</li>
<li>The users of the model should be involved in model construction from its conceptualization to each implementation to ensure that a high degree of realism is built into the model through reasonable assumption regarding system structure and reliable data.</li>
<li>Sensitivity model can also be used to check model face validity.</li>
<li>The model users are asked to if the model behaves in the expected way when one or more input variable is changed.</li>
</ul>
<p>b. <strong>Validating input &#8211; output transformation</strong>:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>View the model as a black box and feed the input at one end and examine the output at other end.</li>
<li>Use the same input for real system, compare the output with the model output.</li>
<li>If they dit closely, the vlack box seems working fine, otherwise something is wrong.</li>
</ul>
<p>c. <strong>Introduction to Accreditation of models</strong> :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Model accreditation is an official determination that a model is acceptable for a specific purpose. Accreditation certifies that the element being accredited meets given standards. For a model, accreditation must be done with respect to the model&#8217;s explicit specification and the demonstration that the computer based model does or does not meet the specifications.</li>
<li>This demonstration is the responsibility of the model developers, who must show that their work passes developer acceptance tests. If the modeling process was done properly and of appropriate documentation was done , then accreditation of model for its specified user should follow.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Why confidence interval is needed in the analysis of simulation output ? How can we establish a confidence interval ?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In the analysis of simulation output, confidence interval is needed because it provide us with upper and lower limit on sample mean, and with this interval we can then be confident we have captured the population mean. The lower limit and upper limit around our sample mean tells us the range of values that our true population mean is likely to lie within.</p>
<p>We can establish confidence interval as follow :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Identify a sample statistic (eg : sample mean, same proportion) that we will use to estimate a population parameter.</li>
<li>Select a confidence level. We can choose 90%, 95%, 99%.</li>
<li>Find the margin of error. It is calculated as margin of error. It is calculated as :</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;">margin of error = Critical value * standard deviation</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">OR</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">margin of error = Critical value * standard error</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>specify the confidence interval as :</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;">Confidence interval = sample statistic ± margin of error</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes on :</p>
<ol>
<li> Non-Stationary Poission process</li>
<li>Feedback system</li>
</ol>
<p> </p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
<li><strong> Non-Stationary Poission process</strong> :A Poisson process is a stochastic process that represents the occurrence of events in continuous time. The standard Poisson process has the property of stationarity, meaning that the rate of event occurrences remains constant over time. However, in some scenarios, the rate may vary with time, leading to the concept of a non-stationary Poisson process.<em><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Characteristics of Non-Stationary Poisson Process:</span></em>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Time-Varying Intensity (Rate): </span>Unlike the stationary Poisson process where the intensity remains constant, a non-stationary Poisson process allows the event rate to change over time.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Intensity Function:</span> The intensity function, often denoted by <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">λ</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span></span>, specifies the time-varying rate of events. It represents the instantaneous rate of events at time <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span></span></span></span></span>.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Random Events:</span> Events still occur randomly, and the time between events follows an exponential distribution.</li>
</ol>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><em>Mathematical Representation:</em></span></p>
<p>The probability of observing <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">k</span></span></span></span></span> events in a small time interval <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">Δ</span><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span></span></span></span></span> is given by:</p>
<p><span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">N</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">Δ</span><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">−</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">N</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mrel">=</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">k</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mrel">=(</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mopen mtight">[</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">λ</span><span class="mopen mtight">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">t</span><span class="mclose mtight">)</span><span class="mbin mtight">⋅</span>Δ<span class="mord mathnormal mtight">t</span><span class="mclose mtight">]<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">k</span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mbin mtight">⋅</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">e</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight">−<span class="mord mathnormal mtight">λ</span><span class="mopen mtight">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">t</span><span class="mclose mtight">)</span><span class="mbin mtight">⋅</span>Δ<span class="mord mathnormal mtight">t</span></span></span></span></sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">) / k<span class="mclose mtight">!</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>where <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">)</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">N</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span></span> is the number of events up to time <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>
<p>Non-stationary Poisson processes find applications in various fields, including telecommunications, finance, and healthcare, where event rates may be influenced by external factors.</li>
<li><strong>Feedback system</strong> :A feedback system is a system in which the output of the system is fed back to the input, influencing the subsequent behavior of the system. Feedback can either be positive or negative, depending on whether the output reinforces or counteracts the input. Feedback mechanisms are common in various fields, including engineering, biology, economics, and control systems. <img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-39376 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/feedback-system.drawio.png?resize=565%2C207&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="565" height="207"><em><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Types of Feedback:</span></em>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><em><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Positive Feedback:</span></em>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>In positive feedback, the output enhances or amplifies the input, leading to a self-reinforcing loop. This can result in exponential growth or destabilization of the system.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><em> Negative Feedback:</em></span>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>In negative feedback, the output opposes or reduces the input, maintaining stability and equilibrium in the system. Negative feedback loops are common in homeostatic systems.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
